We fitted a Bayesian logistic model (estimated using MCMC sampling with 4 chains of 2000 iterations and a warmup of 1000) to predict class with Attr24, Attr25, Attr26, Attr34, Attr5 and Attr46 (formula = class ~ Attr24 + Attr25 + Attr26 + Attr34 + Attr5 + Attr46). Priors over parameters were all set as student_t (location = 0.00, scale = 2.50) distributions. The Region of Practical Equivalence (ROPE) percentage was defined as the proportion of the posterior distribution within the [-0.18, 0.18] range. The 89% Credible Intervals (CIs) were based on Highest Density Intervals (HDI). Parameters were scaled by the mean and the SD of the response variable. We fitted a Bayesian logistic model (estimated using MCMC sampling with 4 chains of 2000 iterations and a warmup of 1000) to predict class with Attr8, Attr10, Attr12, Attr20, Attr33, Attr40, Attr42, Attr46, Attr49, Attr59, Attr63 and Attr64 (formula = class ~ Attr8 + Attr10 + Attr12 + Attr20 + Attr33 + Attr40 + Attr42 + Attr46 + Attr49 + Attr59 + Attr63 + Attr64). Priors over parameters were all set as student_t (location = 0.00, scale = 2.50) distributions. The Region of Practical Equivalence (ROPE) percentage was defined as the proportion of the posterior distribution within the [-0.18, 0.18] range. The 89% Credible Intervals (CIs) were based on Highest Density Intervals (HDI). Parameters were scaled by the mean and the SD of the response variable.
